<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: COUNCIL VOTES TO ENACT OPEN-MEETING LAW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Los Angeles City Council, acknowledging the importance of public input, 
voted Tuesday to enact its own version of California's open-meeting law, which 
was recently suspended. 
</P>
<P>
After several minutes of congratulating themselves on their fair-mindedness, 
the council members voted 11 to 0 to draw up an ordinance resembling the Brown 
Act, which was suspended for a year by state budget writers as a cost-saving 
measure. 
</P>
<P>
The act required local governments, including city councils and boards of 
supervisors, to post an agenda 72 hours before a meeting, follow that agenda 
and allow time for public comments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
