<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080890-0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 258502 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 8, 1990, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 6; Column 6; Letters Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
63 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ASIAN IMMIGRANTS IN PACIFIC RIM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is true some new immigrants cannot adapt themselves to the American way of 
life instantly and sometimes cut down trees in their gardens and build walls 
around their houses. 
</P>
<P>
The walls are intended to ensure security, not privacy as Gibson has said. When 
they live here longer and know their environment better, they will give up such 
practices. 
</P>
<P>
KENT YANG 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
