<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: MOVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rated A: The New York Times has accepted an ad for a movie that carries an 
adults-only rating assigned to it by its own distributor. 
</P>
<P>
Wayne Wang's "Life Is Cheap . . . But Toilet Paper Is Expensive" was rated X by 
the Motion Picture Assn. of America, but Silverlight Entertainment, arguing 
that the X creates an undue economic hardship on films, put its own "A" label 
-- for adults only -- on the ad and submitted it to the New York Times. The 
newspaper has in recent years rejected ads for X-rated movies, but has run ads 
for films that went out unrated. "Life Is Cheap" opens in New York on Aug. 24 
and in Los Angeles in September. GREG BRAXTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080890-0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 258583 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 8, 1990, Wednesday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 2; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
796 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHILDREN'S THEATER REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
'LI'L ABNER' OFFERS RELIEF FROM FAST-LANE LIFE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CORINNE FLOCKEN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BREA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Forget Martinique. If Orange County's hectic lifestyle is a gettin' you down, 
pack up the chillun and escape to Dogpatch, U.S.A., a town that moves slower 
than maple syrup a-slidin' down a stack of hot cakes. 
</P>
<P>
This weekend, Dogpatch comes to Brea's Curtis Theatre via "Li'l Abner," a 
"Hee-Haw"-style family musical presented by the Brea Youth Theatre under the 
direction of Gregory and Kysa Cohen. Closing performances are scheduled 
Thursday through Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
Created in 1956 by Norman Panama and Melvin Frank, the stage version of "Li'l 
Abner" is based on Al Capp's syndicated comic strip of the same name, which 
premiered in 1934 and ran a whopping 44 years. 
</P>
<P>
Things haven't changed much in Dogpatch. Daisy Mae is still mooning over Abner, 
Mammy Yokum still runs the roost and "most everybody else can still be found 
lazin' around the fishin' hole and moochin' a little moonshine." 
</P>
<P>
But, there's trouble a-brewin'. It seems the worthy Senator Phogbound has 
proclaimed Dogpatch to be the "most worthless town in the whole U.S. of A.," 
earning it the right to be blown off the map in an A-bomb test. This would be 
just fine with the residents, if it didn't interfere with the annual Sadie 
Hawkins Day race, in which members of the fairer sex (and in Dogpatch, you use 
that term loosely) nab unwilling husbands. 
</P>
<P>
The search for something -- anything -- to make Dogpatch worthwhile turns up 
Yokumberry tonic, the secret elixir that has made Abner the strapping youth he 
is. Government types whisk the boy and the brew off to Washington for extensive 
testing, setting the stage for lots of jolly jabs at Big Business and dimwitted 
politicians. (There's a not-too-subtle irony in that this "Abner" plays inside 
Brea's slick Civic and Cultural Center, just a stone's throw from the city's 
seat of power.) 
</P>
<P>
"Abner" features a 36-member cast of area youngsters, ages 8 to 17. The kids 
have varying degrees of theatrical and vocal expertise, but all put out equal 
shares of energy and enthusiasm. 
</P>
<P>
Kristyn Jenkins, 10, is the real standout as the sassy Mammy Yokum, hobbling 
madly about the stage, barking orders between puffs on her corncob pipe. Doug 
Book, 17, falls short as a singer, but his portrayal of the loveable country 
hunk Abner is larger than life. Wendy See, 15, is slim, blond and has a sweet 
soprano, making her a winsome Daisy Mae. And Roger Alan Ross, 15, is a slippery 
Marryin' Sam, a fast-talking huckster with more dee-lux wedding packages up his 
sleeve than a Vegas chapel. Eric Bleau, 14, plays Earthquake McGoon, a solid 
block wall of a man with an intellect to match. 
</P>
<P>
The opening number, "It's a Typical Day," is meant to introduce several of the 
minor roles, but the overamplified background music made it tough to make out 
the lyrics. Additionally, the program lists the cast alphabetically, instead of 
in order of appearance, making it harder to identify cast members. 
</P>
<P>
Musically speaking, however, things do improve later in the show. "Jubilation 
T. Cornpone" and "The Country's in the Very Best of Hands" are a couple of 
rousing numbers highlighted with some surprisingly tight dancing. And "Love in 
a Home" is a tender duet between Abner and Daisy Mae that shows off See's 
honeyed voice. 
</P>
<P>
Sets and lighting by Trent Nelson are serviceable and allow the large cast 
plenty of room to whoop it up on the theater's expansive stage. Annie 
McQuitty's costumes ape Capp's original drawings, down to Abner's single-strap 
overalls and Daisy's polka-dot blouse (See chose to wear hers a little more 
modestly than the comic strip's original, amply-endowed Daisy); and Senator 
Phogbound's 40-gallon Uncle Sam hat was a hoot. 
</P>
<P>
According to program director D. Scott Riordan, the Brea Youth Theatre has 
operated under various names and directors for the last six years, presenting 
one family musical each summer in the Curtis Theatre. The city took over the 
program in 1988, bringing in local directors, designers and choreographers to 
stage each show. Participation is open to any student in the county, but the 
bulk of the casts are made up of children from the Brea, Yorba Linda and 
Fullerton areas. 
</P>
<P>
'LI'L ABNER' 
</P>
<P>
A Brea Youth Theatre production of the Norman Panama/Melvin Frank musical. 
Based on the comic strip by Al Capp. Directed by Gregory and Kysa Cohen. Runs 2 
hours and 30 minutes, with one intermission. With Eric Bleau, Doug Cook, Adam 
de la Pena, Justin Dickson, Kristyn Jenkins, Roger Alan Ross and Wendy See. 
Sets and lighting by Trent Nelson. Costumes by Annie McQuitty. Audio design by 
Jenson Crawford. Performances are Thursday and Friday at 7:30 p.m., Saturday at 
2 and 7:30 p.m., Sunday at 2 p.m. in the Curtis Theatre, Brea Civic and 
Cultural Center, 1 Civic Center Circle, Brea. Tickets: $6 to $7. Information: 
(714) 990-7722. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, "Li'l Abner" in Brea features a 36-member cast of area youngsters, ages 
8 to 17, with varying theatrical and vocal expertise. JOHN FUNG / Los Angeles 
Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Play Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA080890-0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 258584 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 8, 1990, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 2; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
651 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVIE REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
'TWISTER': A KANSAS QUITE UNLIKE DOROTHY'S 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Michael Almereyda's "Twister" (at the Nuart) is set in a modern boozy Kansas, 
where flaky rich kids float off on a sea of alcohol and boredom. It's a movie 
with a slight buzz on: a charming, trance-like fantasy soggily alive to strange 
spasms and tics of character. 
</P>
<P>
First-time director Almereyda based this movie on Mary Robison's 1980 novel 
"Oh" -- which the writer says is about "the frailty of adulthood, the frailty 
of love. " That describes the plight of most of the central characters seem 
arrested in adolescence, especially siblings Maureen and Howdy Cleveland (Suzy 
Amis and Crispin Glover). Unwed mother Maureen, or "Mo," has the face of a 
corn-silk Botticelli with a spray of Sissy Spacek freckles. She's given to 
slouching, tantrums, petulant pouts. 
</P>
<P>
Brother Howdy is the real oddball: dressed in black with fluttery eyes and 
Renaissance bangs, he's given to cracking whips, striking Byronic poses and 
droning awful self-composed dirges that try to fuse new-wave rock with Gaelic 
poetry ("Daddy was mean" is his main theme). Howdy is an "artist" the way many 
bored, bright, lazy, self-indulgent rich kids are artists: their writing, 
painting or movies are just like his "songs." And Glover makes him a classic 
poseur-hysteric: fracturing his delivery so hilariously that every word is 
filigreed to death and every gesture is a goony ballet. In "River's Edge," 
those flailing, eccentric emphasises sometimes seemed a little forced. Here, 
they fit perfectly; it's his best performance. 
</P>
<P>
The Cleveland kids' dad, Eugene the soda pop king is played by Harry Dean 
Stanton with almost hair-raising delicacy and control: as someone so inured to 
his family -- or so soused himself -- that he's beyond amazement. He reacts to 
everything with the same crocked twinkle and amiable mellow-tone. When he 
finally throws a tantrum, it has a horrific daintiness: With quiet ferocity, he 
overturns three soup bowls and sternly tells everyone to continue eating. 
</P>
<P>
Like Dorothy, the characters including Mo's ex-lover (Dylan McDermott) and a 
bemused black maid (Charlaine Woodard) suffer through a tornado. But it doesn't 
spin them into any magic kingdom. They simply wake up dazed again, in another 
unbearably unstructured day. What Almereyda has drawn here -- with a mood that, 
except for its absence of zoom shots, irresistibly recalls the vaguely 
narcotized, real-surreal atmosphere of Robert Altman's '70s films -- is the 
dilemma of a family sunk in riches and without a clue what to do with them. 
</P>
<P>
Setting the movie in Kansas -- that flat land of pale skies, with its echoes of 
both Oz and "In Cold Blood" -- heightens the surreality. It suggests the magic 
that won't come, the terror that might. When William Burroughs shows up, taking 
target practice and then ruminating on an acquaintance who shot horses and died 
after trying to eat a clock, it's a good sample of "Twister's" humor: 
ultra-deadpan, a little mean: American Gothic with glazed eyes. 
</P>
<P>
Almereyda fills every scene with verbal jolts and spins, but he doesn't have 
much visual style. The film suffers from a lack of modulation, and also from 
the low budget that keeps Almereyda from even trying for a simulated hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
But "Twister's" shortcomings can be excused, because it has something new to 
offer: a goofball penetration into the lives of the rich and tipsy, 
half-crocked under the rainbow. Seldom does a movie seem so tied to the moods 
and fluctuations of alcohol. Watching these people, you can almost imagine what 
they're drinking: from Chris' six-packs to Mo's whiskey and pills to Dad's 
bourbon to whatever Howdy is doodling himself up with: perhaps creme de menthe 
laced with Methedrine. 
</P>
<P>
"Twister" (rated PG-13) may not have special effects or taut structure, but it 
has something movies with real-looking tornadoes usually miss: intelligence, 
surprise, a flair for the craziness of the everyday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Motion Picture Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
