<HEADLINE>
<P>
O.C. MOTORISTS BLAME BIG OIL FOR 10-CENT AVERAGE RISE IN GAS PRICES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TONY MARCANO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At a congressional hearing in Washington on Tuesday, a Nevada senator said the 
American public is "mad as hell" at sharply rising gasoline prices. In Orange 
County, consumers were indeed mad, but they weren't the least bit surprised. 
</P>
<P>
Motorists interviewed at gas pumps Tuesday said they expected the nation's oil 
companies to take advantage of the Middle East crisis by convincing consumers 
that oil supplies are dwindling. But motorist Franco Ferretti was not buying 
it. 
</P>
<P>
"The oil companies are not overcharging the people -- they're ripping off the 
people," Ferretti, a Huntington Beach resident, said as he filled his pickup at 
a Costa Mesa Shell station. "This whole thing in the Middle East looks like a 
setup on the part of the oil companies to me." 
</P>
<P>
Ferretti said his two-mile daily commute means that the price increase will 
have only a negligible effect on his income. Not so for commuter Danny Palmer. 
</P>
<P>
"I commute from Mission Viejo to Huntington Beach every day," Palmer said. "I 
have a Chevy truck that holds 20 to 25 gallons, so I'm going to notice it." 
</P>
<P>
Palmer and other South County residents are going to notice the price increase 
a bit more than other county consumers, according to a random survey conducted 
by The Times. 
</P>
<P>
The survey of 21 stations revealed an average price of $1.25 for a gallon of 
unleaded gasoline Tuesday at self-serve pumps in South County stations; the 
average price in Central County was $1.20 a gallon, about $1.23 in North 
County. In all regions, prices were up since July 31 an average of 10 cents a 
gallon -- including a new 5-cent-per-gallon surcharge levied by the state. 
</P>
<P>
Prices were even higher for premium unleaded and diesel fuel. Premium prices 
soared past $1.40 a gallon at some stations, and diesel fuel prices were up as 
much as 8 cents a gallons since the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
"I think it is outrageous," said Jodi Holland, a Huntington Beach resident, 
while her diesel-fueled Mercedes-Benz was being filled at a Huntington Beach 
Texaco station. "I have to mortgage my house so I can pay the credit card 
bill." 
</P>
<P>
The Times survey also showed that prices in the same parts of the county varied 
by up to 11 cents a gallon among gas stations. Jim Daskal, general counsel and 
director of government relations for the Washington-based Service Station 
Dealers of America, attributed the disparity to wild price fluctuations over 
the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
"With prices changing almost hourly. . . . you have situations where 10 dealers 
of the same brand could pay six different (wholesale) prices," Daskal said. "It 
depends on when they bought it. Over the weekend, we saw some 7- or 8-cent 
differences between ordering on Sunday evening or Monday morning." 
</P>
<P>
Daskal said service station owners have reported that the western states, 
including California, have been hit hardest by the increases, which he said 
"makes absolutely no sense, considering most of the crude sold in the Southland 
is coming from Alaska." 
</P>
<P>
Despite the increases, Daskal said, his organization has received few reports 
of consumers directing their anger toward station owners, who contend that they 
are making little profit while the oil companies are raking in millions. 
</P>
<P>
"The customers have been in this situation before, and they expect things like 
this to happen," said Avo Asyan, owner of Avo's Shell in Costa Mesa. "We don't 
control the prices. The oil companies and the suppliers control the prices." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
GASOLINE PRICES AT VARIOUS O.C. LOCATIONS 
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices in Orange County have increased an average of 10 in the past 
week, due to both the crisis in the Middle East and a 5 state tax hike that 
took effect last Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Prices are for one gallon of self-serve, unleaded gasoline paid for with cash. 
They are rounded up to the nearest penny. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
