<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
JAPANESE TESTING AIDS DRUG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Japanese consortium said today it has developed an agent that may be useful 
in destroying cells infected by the AIDS virus. 
</P>
<P>
In test-tube experiments, the agent destroyed 90% of cells infected by the 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus, said a spokesman for Sumitomo 
Chemical, one of the partners in the consortium. 
</P>
<P>
The other partners are soft-drink maker Calpis Food Industry and Hokkaido 
University. 
</P>
<P>
The agent is composed of ribosome, made from phosphorus liptide and 
cholesterol, and a peptide of the protein film CD4. 
</P>
<P>
A scientist at Hokkaido University said the agent was designed to destroy only 
AIDS-infected cells and would not affect normal cells. 
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo is in charge of further development and hopes to start clinical tests 
in the United States within the year, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
