<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: TRUMP'S 'CRYPTO-NAZI' CONNECTION STIRS GOSSIP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EVERYBODY'S TALKING about Marie Brenner's interview in Vanity Fair, especially 
that concerning Donald Trump's manner of having glided over his German 
ancestors. (It's true that reporter James Revson laid all this out in his 
Newsday column months ago, but Marie has revived it with an added dash of 
spice.) To wit, that Donald appears to take aspects of his German background 
seriously. 
</P>
<P>
John Walter works for the Trump organization and when he visits Donald in his 
office, Ivana told a family friend, he clicks his heels and says, "Heil 
Hitler," possibly as a family joke. 
</P>
<P>
Reporter Brenner lays out the details of a somewhat amazing story that has been 
making the rounds but, to my knowledge, was never nailed down before; a story 
to the effect that Trump reads from a book of Hitler's collected speeches, 
having kept the work "My New Order" in a cabinet by his bed. (A copy of this is 
also now in the office of Ivana's lawyer, Michael Kennedy, "as if it were a 
grenade.") Brenner notes that Hitler was a master propagandist and that Trump 
has followed in his footsteps, at least in this regard. She calls his habit of 
exaggeration and prevarication "the big lie," and notes that if one keeps 
reiterating something, then some people will finally come to believe it. 
</P>
<P>
WHEN MARIE bearded Trump in his den on this issue, he said that it was his 
friend Marty Davis of Paramount Pictures who'd given him a copy of "Mein Kampf" 
and he's a Jew. Davis says he didn't give Trump "Mein Kampf," but the aforesaid 
"My New Order." "I thought he would find it interesting. I am his friend, but 
I'm not Jewish." 
</P>
<P>
Trump told Brenner, "If I had these speeches, and I am not saying that I do, I 
would never read them." It is left for Brenner to ask if perhaps Ivana is 
hoping to convince her friends and her lawyers that her husband "is a 
crypto-Nazi." 
</P>
<P>
Brenner describes Ivana as having become something like her husband -- "a 
double agent, able to project innocence and utter confidence." And she quotes 
Kennedy, describing his beautiful client as suffering from the "Stockholm 
syndrome" -- meaning that "she had the mentality of a captive. After a while 
she couldn't fight her captor anymore and began to identify with him. Ivana is 
deaf, dumb and blind when it comes to Donald." 
</P>
<P>
ONE THING you'll be able to pick up from this magazine story is Trump's 
attitude today. 
</P>
<P>
Brenner quotes a Trump attorney as saying: "Donald's very up. This is the kind 
of challenge Donald likes. It's weird. You would never know anything is wrong." 
</P>
</TEXT>
