<HEADLINE>
<P>
NAMES IN THE NEWS; 
</P>
<P>
ME AND ROGER AND 325 OTHERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DETROIT 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Singers Steve Lawrence and Eydie Gorme helped retired General Motors Corp. 
Chairman Roger B. Smith say goodby to hundreds of friends at an opulent bash 
featuring smoked duck and $120-a-bottle champagne. 
</P>
<P>
"It was one of the most elegant functions like that that I've ever attended, 
and I've been to quite a few," said David Cole, a University of Michigan 
official and son of the late Edward Cole, former president of GM. 
</P>
<P>
"I would have traded my salary for what it would have cost to put that on," 
Cole said. "I'm sure it was an expensive proposition." 
</P>
<P>
Sunday's get-together became known as "the $5-million party." GM officials said 
that figure was "ridiculous," but declined to say how much it cost. 
</P>
<P>
"This is the usual party we have for retiring top executives," GM spokesman Jim 
Crellin said. 
</P>
<P>
There were 326 people on the guest list, including seven of Forbes magazine's 
400 richest people in America. No one from Ford Motor Co. nor Chrysler Corp. 
was there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
